@ivankelly I actually changed to the X3 root certs since this is the actual certs used to sign the certificates as explained in https://letsencrypt.org/certificates/ 

That is also the CA cert bundled in Chrome and Firefox.

I verified this works by doing: 

```java
PulsarClient client = PulsarClient.builder()
                .serviceUrl("pulsar+ssl://letsencrypt.org:443")
                .build();

Producer<byte[]> producer  = client.newProducer().topic("test-topic").create();
```

@rdhabalia @merlimat 
I think we can control the redelivery-tracker by client side.
If user enable the DLQ feature, broker will enable redelivery-tracker. If not, disable redelivery-tracker.

@sijie @merlimat I think this pr should be reviewed very carefully. IMHO #3155 could exist without this change, maybe with a warning to the user about publish time being client generated.
We discussed about delayed messages on dev mailing list and I think it would be great if we (especially all of you the leaders) could get general consensus if we want #3155 to be on pulsar or not.

Thanks!

@hrsakai is this on a single topic? The histogram points to there being a lot of entries in the ManagedCursorContainer. There should only be one managed cursor for deduplication for each topic. So either something is triggering the creation and destruction of the dedupe cursors in a loop, or something about having any dedupe cursor at all is causing bad behaviour from the other cursors.

Can you try enabling debug logging for org.apache.pulsar.broker.service.persistent.MessageDeduplication?

If that doesn't yield info, then we'll have to do a heap dump.
